HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 780
By Reneau
A RESOLUTION to propose an amendment to Article XI of the
Constitution of Tennessee, relative to the right to
food.
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that a majority of all the members of each house concurring, as shown by the
yeas and nays entered on their journals, that it is proposed that Article XI of the Constitution of
the State of Tennessee be amended by adding the following language as a new section:
All individuals have a natural, inherent, and unalienable right to save and
exchange seeds; and to acquire and consume the food of their own choosing, as long as
an individual does not commit trespassing, theft, poaching, or other abuses of private
property rights, public lands, or natural resources in the acquisition of seeds or food.
All individuals have the right to grow, raise, harvest, and produce the food of their
own choosing on land that is not zoned for a particular use, or that is zoned for
agricultural or residential use, or that is zoned for a mixture of uses that includes
agricultural or residential use, by the local government entity that is authorized by law to
zone such land, as long as an individual does not commit trespassing, theft, poaching, or
other abuses of private property rights, public lands, or natural resources in the
harvesting, production, or acquisition of food.
The recognition of these rights does not limit the state's power to regulate or
prohibit the possession of seeds, and the growth, raising, and harvesting of plants, from
which controlled and illegal substances are produced.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that the foregoing amendment be referred to the One
Hundred Fifteenth General Assembly and that this resolution proposing such amendment be
